    Note over Alice,Network: ═══════════ ITC CAUSALITY TRACKING ═══════════

    rect rgb(250, 245, 255)
        Note over Alice,Network: 🕐 INTERVAL TREE CLOCKS (ITC) - Distributed Causality:<br/><br/>WHY ITC INSTEAD OF TIMESTAMPS:<br/>  Simple timestamps have problems:<br/>  ❌ Clock skew between entities<br/>  ❌ Can't detect concurrent updates<br/>  ❌ Can't resolve conflicts automatically<br/>  ❌ Vector clocks need O(n) space<br/><br/>ITC BENEFITS:<br/>  ✅ O(log n) space complexity (vs O(n) vector clocks)<br/>  ✅ Detects happens-before relationships<br/>  ✅ Detects concurrent updates (conflicts)<br/>  ✅ No clock synchronization needed<br/>  ✅ Fork/join for dynamic entity set<br/><br/>ITC STRUCTURE:<br/>  itc_stamp = {<br/>    id: ID_component,      // Fork/join operations<br/>    event: Event_component // Logical counter (tree)<br/>  }<br/><br/>  ID space examples:<br/>  - Alice: {l: 1, r: 0, 0, 0} (left quadrant)<br/>  - Bob:   {l: 0, r: 1, 0, 0} (right-left quadrant)<br/>  - Carol: {l: 0, 0, r: 1, 0} (right-right-left)<br/>  - Kitchen: {l: 0, 0, 0, r: 1} (right-right-right)<br/><br/>OPERATIONS:<br/><br/>1. FORK (New Entity Joins):<br/>   - Split ID space with existing entity<br/>   - Each gets portion of ID space<br/>   - Event counter starts at 0<br/><br/>2. EVENT (Local Update):<br/>   - Increment event counter: event++<br/>   - Publish with new stamp<br/>   - Establishes happens-after ordering<br/><br/>3. JOIN (Sync with Other Entity):<br/>   - Merge event counters<br/>   - Reunite ID spaces (optional)<br/>   - Creates happens-after relationship<br/><br/>CAUSALITY DETECTION:<br/><br/>  Compare stamps A and B:<br/>  <br/>  IF event_A dominates event_B:<br/>    → A happened-before B (causally ordered)<br/>    → B must incorporate A's changes<br/>    → No conflict<br/>  <br/>  IF event_B dominates event_A:<br/>    → B happened-before A<br/>    → A already incorporates B<br/>    → No conflict<br/>  <br/>  IF neither dominates:<br/>    → Concurrent updates detected!<br/>    → Conflict resolution needed<br/>    → Use merge strategy (semantic, LWW, etc.)<br/><br/>PROTOCOL USAGE:<br/><br/>  Every publish operation includes ITC stamp:<br/>  - Tree updates: stamp.event++<br/>  - Offer records: stamp.event++<br/>  - Acceptance records: stamp.event++<br/>  - Satisfaction records: stamp.event++<br/><br/>  Entities can:<br/>  ✅ Detect if update is stale (happened-before current)<br/>  ✅ Detect if update is new (happened-after current)<br/>  ✅ Detect if update is concurrent (conflict)<br/>  ✅ Resolve conflicts deterministically<br/><br/>EXAMPLE CONCURRENT UPDATE:<br/><br/>  Alice publishes tree: {event: 3}<br/>  Bob publishes tree: {event: 3} (concurrently)<br/>  <br/>  Neither event dominates → concurrent!<br/>  <br/>  Resolution strategy:<br/>  - Semantic merge (combine trees intelligently)<br/>  - ID-based ordering (deterministic tiebreaker)<br/>  - Last-Writer-Wins (use wall-clock as hint)<br/>  - User prompt (manual resolution)<br/><br/>💡 ITC enables truly distributed, conflict-aware protocol!
    end

    Note over Alice,Network: ═══════════ TWO-TIER ALLOCATION RATIONALE ═══════════

    rect rgb(255, 250, 245)
        Note over Alice,Network: 🎯 WHY TWO-TIER? (Matches structure.md)<br/><br/>TIER 1: MUTUAL PRIORITY (MS > 0)<br/>  Recipients where BOTH parties recognize each other<br/>  Gets first access to capacity<br/><br/>  Benefits:<br/>  ✅ Incentivizes mutual relationships<br/>  ✅ Rewards reciprocity<br/>  ✅ Priority to established partnerships<br/>  ✅ More stable allocations<br/><br/>  Example:<br/>  - Carol recognizes Alice (30%)<br/>  - Alice recognizes Carol (30%)<br/>  - MS(Carol, Alice) = 30% × 30% = 0.09 > 0<br/>  → Alice gets Tier 1 priority!<br/><br/>TIER 2: UNILATERAL RECOGNITION (MS = 0)<br/>  Recipients where only provider recognizes them<br/>  Gets remaining capacity after Tier 1<br/><br/>  Benefits:<br/>  ✅ Allows one-way generosity<br/>  ✅ Enables bootstrapping new relationships<br/>  ✅ Provider can help strangers<br/>  ✅ Still respects mutual relationships first<br/><br/>  Example:<br/>  - Carol recognizes Dave (20%)<br/>  - Dave doesn't recognize Carol yet (0%)<br/>  - MS(Carol, Dave) = 20% × 0% = 0<br/>  → Dave gets Tier 2 (if capacity remains)<br/><br/>KEY INSIGHT:<br/><br/>  Without two-tier:<br/>  - One-way recognition treated same as mutual<br/>  - No incentive for reciprocity<br/>  - Mutual relationships don't get priority<br/><br/>  With two-tier:<br/>  - Mutual relationships prioritized (Tier 1)<br/>  - One-way generosity still possible (Tier 2)<br/>  - System incentivizes building mutual trust<br/>  - More realistic social dynamics<br/><br/>MATHEMATICAL FORMULATION:<br/><br/>  Tier 1 (Mutual Priority):<br/>    mutual_recipients = {r : MS(p,r) > 0}<br/>    allocation[r] = capacity × (MS(p,r) / Σ MS)<br/>  <br/>  Tier 2 (Unilateral Recognition):<br/>    remaining = capacity - Σ tier1_allocations<br/>    unilateral = {r : MS(p,r) = 0 AND recognition[p→r] > 0}<br/>    allocation[r] = remaining × (recognition[p→r] / Σ recognition)<br/><br/>💡 Matches structure.md implementation exactly!<br/>   Protocol now reflects what implementations actually do!
    end

    Note over Alice,Network: ═══════════ IMPLEMENTATION NOTES ═══════════

    rect rgb(250, 250, 230)
        Note over Alice,Network: 💻 KEY IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS:<br/><br/>1. INDEPENDENT COMPUTATION:<br/>   - Each provider computes allocations independently<br/>   - Same deterministic algorithm (5 steps)<br/>   - No coordination, no central server<br/>   - Results should match if inputs match<br/><br/>2. ALLOCATION → OFFER SEPARATION:<br/>   - Allocation = derived state (MS formula)<br/>   - Offer = allocation × offering_policy<br/>   - offering_policy: {commitment_rate, auto_publish}<br/>   - commitment_rate: 0.0-1.0 (default 1.0 = full)<br/>   - auto_publish: true (automatic) | false (manual approval)<br/>   - Provider can adjust commitment without changing algorithm<br/>   - Creates convexity: option to commit less<br/><br/>3. ACCEPT/DECLINE MECHANICS:<br/>   - DEFAULT: Manual per-cycle decisions<br/>   - OPTIONAL: Policy-based automation<br/>   - Offers are proposals, not commitments<br/>   - Recipients have full control<br/>   - Partial acceptance allowed<br/>   - Declined amounts return to provider capacity<br/>   - Update law uses ACCEPTED amounts only<br/><br/>4. ACCEPTANCE POLICY (Optional):<br/>   - Part of tree structure (user input)<br/>   - acceptance_policy: {strategy, auto_accept}<br/>   - strategy: "manual" | "1/N" | "weighted" | "greedy"<br/>   - auto_accept: false (manual) | true (automatic)<br/>   - Can be updated anytime (part of tree)<br/><br/>5. ACCEPTANCE STRATEGY IMPLEMENTATION:<br/>   - 1/N: target = need/N, accept min(offer, target) each<br/>   - weighted: weight = reputation/Σ, accept need×weight<br/>   - greedy: sort by reputation, accept best first<br/>   - manual: user reviews each offer<br/><br/>6. OSCILLATION DETECTION:<br/>   - Track 3-point history: N(t-2), N(t-1), N(t)<br/>   - Pattern: N(t-2) > 0, N(t-1) = 0, N(t) ≈ N(t-2)<br/>   - Threshold: |N(t) - N(t-2)| / N(t-2) < 0.2<br/>   - Damping factor: 0.7 (tunable parameter)<br/>   - Per-recipient, per-resource-type<br/><br/>7. SATISFACTION WEIGHTING:<br/>   - Bootstrap: recognition only (share = recognition)<br/>   - With data: MS = MR × recipient_share<br/>   - recipient_share = learned from satisfaction<br/>   - Derived from: recognition × provider_capacity_sat<br/>   - Normalized across all eligible providers<br/><br/>8. CONVERGENCE MONITORING:<br/>   - Track: Σ all needs over time<br/>   - Should decrease monotonically<br/>   - Typical: 5-10 cycles to convergence<br/>   - With damping: smoother, faster convergence<br/>   - Alert if oscillation persists (tune damping)<br/><br/>9. DATA STRUCTURES:<br/>   - Tree: {recognition, offering_policy, acceptance_policy, needs, capacities}<br/>   - DerivedState: ephemeral, keyed by node_id<br/>   - ITCStamp: {id: ID_component, event: Event_component}<br/>   - OfferRecord: {id, itc_stamp, provider, offers: [{to, qty, tier}]}<br/>   - AcceptanceRecord: {id, itc_stamp, offer_id, acceptances: [{offer, accepted, declined}]}<br/>   - SatisfactionRecord: {id, itc_stamp, ratings: [{offer, satisfaction}]}<br/>   - TreeUpdate: {tree_id, itc_stamp, needs, capacities, ...}<br/>   - All records published to network (event stream with causality)<br/><br/>10. TWO-TIER ALLOCATION:<br/>   - Tier 1: Recipients with MS > 0 (mutual recognition)<br/>   - Tier 2: Recipients with MS = 0 but recognition[p→r] > 0<br/>   - Each offer tagged with tier: "mutual" or "unilateral"<br/>   - Incentivizes mutual relationships<br/>   - Allows one-way generosity with remaining capacity<br/><br/>11. ITC CLOCK MANAGEMENT:<br/>   - Initialize: Fork from seed or existing entity<br/>   - Each publish: Event++ before publishing<br/>   - Store stamp with each published record<br/>   - Compare stamps when observing updates<br/>   - Detect concurrency and resolve conflicts<br/>   - No wall-clock synchronization needed
    end